        Understanding Hydration Guidelines & Biology
      </h3>
      <div class="text-[11px] sm:text-xs text-slate leading-relaxed flex flex-col gap-2.5">
        <p>
          Water makes up about 60% of body weight and is critical for every physiological system. Hydration requirements vary widely:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1 text-slate font-medium">
          <li><strong>Altitude Effects:</strong> Higher altitudes (>5,000 ft) feature lower barometric pressure. Breath rates increase, speeding up evaporation of respiratory moisture. Adjusting your intake upward offsets this.</li>
          <li><strong>Sweat and Intensity:</strong> Sweating rates are highly individual. Professional athletes can lose over 1.5 liters of sweat per hour. Drinking to match sweat rate rather than over-hydrating is key.</li>
          <li><strong>Diuretic Properties:</strong> Caffeine and alcohol trigger temporary urinary frequency, increasing water output. Offsetting diuretic intake prevents chronic mild dehydration.</li>
          <li><strong>Food vs Fluid:</strong> An average person receives about 20% of their daily hydration from moisture in foods (especially raw fruits like watermelon or berries).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-[10px] text-stone mt-1">
          Disclaimer: Hydration targets are estimates. Specific conditions like chronic kidney disease (CKD), congestive heart failure, or severe liver disease restrict fluid intake. Always follow direct directives from a clinical physician.
        </p>
      </div>
